Food debt to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, the trend was higher in November than expected - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were based on only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
In contrast to the US, British, and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the principal. It is felt that the interest rate reduction would facilitate the rise in raw material prices and the slight fall in unemployment.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is located in the Zwickmühle: inflation had to be "absorbed" in order to exclude later needs for action.
At 3.3 per cent, the inflation rate reached a twelve-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area was responsible for rising food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products were also very expensive in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but it is estimated that in 2009 inflation will decrease to 1.9 per cent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts estimate a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts estimate that the ECB will reduce interest rates twice.
