In many places disinfectants are saved
This year more than a thousand infections were detected in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in the hospitals, the overloading of the beds, the overloading of the staff - all factors that are not precisely acceptable to the control of the infections, so the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places the disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalised after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but only a little later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. Since then, an important surgery could not be performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10 this year, multi-resistant pathogen infections were reported from hospitals in 1094 to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, according to Karolina Bröócz, the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark digit should be higher.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the substances are used too high or improperly, they are derived from the well-responsive bacteria antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poor immune system, but also in the elderly, or in patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. Sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital everyday life.
You shouldn't confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA only doesn't exist where she's not being sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks in the supply, and we have the antibiotics needed for treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samplings too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Bröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospitals should examine the patients in question and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
In the Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practised so often.
Not least because there are no grants for this investigation from the State health insurance fund.
Most cases are therefore only likely to occur when the patient already has a remarkable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
On the European Union side, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also directives in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotics should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary so that resistance to the drug cannot arise, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
According to Karolina Bröcz, microbiological samples were even less rare among the outpatients, or patients in the primary care.
To be saved from the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transferred from one patient to another by the caregiver.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks are of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by drip infection or contact, but in the home hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are tied to each other, although there should be an epidemiological distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz points out, unfortunately, in the less financially well-off hospitals it is even apparent that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all the factors that favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are shown to be much less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Bröócz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections in control causes the health insurance huge costs, therefore they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has explained the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
