Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are consulting on the Bali Roadmap, which sets emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
At present, a heated debate is taking place between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate specific figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether the developed countries are ready to support developing countries financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on aid to developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary’s 6 percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" was successful. The Union would even be prepared to commit itself to a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrial states in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to comply with their obligations in terms of strength and accountability.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the aim of the countries which joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its 15 Member States at that time.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will fully comply with, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, whose significance was also highlighted by the IPCC, the International Nobel Peace Prize, the UN Scientific Committee on Climate Change in its recent report.
As a result, emissions reduction would be delayed, and the increase in earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
