Holidays are not everywhere holidays
Holidays in Hungary are regulated precisely by law, so that the practice of redeploying the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year gives us fewer days.
In the EU and in America, too, we see something different as a "day of celebration".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days free of work.
Unemployed days are usually ecclesial holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old, as well as the first day of the new year, are day-free - the latter alone so that the New Year celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are the 15th of March, which is reminiscent of the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the Memorial Day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the founding of the state, on May 1st, celebrates the work, we remember our dead on November 1st and 2nd.
There are also two holidays on Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of the "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before that, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has been set out in his own regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers, public employees and civil servants.
Except for companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays.
This year the working order is only slightly confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formal, as most will take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year, or the special vacation for it.
In the next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redundancies in working days than this year.
The calendar is first set up around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second redeployment will be linked to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, you will have to finish Friday, 24 October in advance.
At the end of the year, however, will remain silent in the sign of the holidays, after everything will lie and stand after December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
