New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being affected.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) is managed by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is very closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
Previous conflict between the two countries reduced deliveries to the EU countries last year.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state of gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more because the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in discussions," said Ukraine's Minister of Economic Affairs Anatoli Kinakh of the Reuters news agency.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] across Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a case of exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas is one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas deposits, but much of them remain underdeveloped.
The consequence is that Gazprom complements its own supplies of gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service has to improve the controls of the pre-criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body outside.
The recommendation of the main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought in Scotland in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish public health service did not have a precise idea of the number of his foreign staff.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a ground car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at Old Bailey in October and was charged with the suspected car bomb attack in Britain.
It is expected that the public health service will carry out checks prior to the appointment of foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the Chief Examiner now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Executive Board should take up guidelines on criminal records that help employers to control in different countries.
"Although we have found references to these controls in some staff documents, they have not been carried out routinely," the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation guidelines with a high degree before the appointment, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that precise information on the number of foreign health service staff is available."
BMA Schottland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in advance of the appointment of potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit the future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that the NHS Scotland's current pre-recruitment tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the Financial Controller warned that the number is probably higher, also because the Boards have problems identifying those employees who are on leave for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued to show that established control procedures were largely complied with by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its pre-employment policies and guidelines for foreign personnel in the NHS.
