Data from an orbital European spaceship show that the planet resembles an averse twin of the Earth even more than was previously known.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to the earth.
The two worlds have about the same size and similar planetary orbits, but the Venus of the Sun is somewhat closer.
Billions of years ago, there would have been conditions on Venus that would have been very similar to those on earth and could have even been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbraked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rate of rotation, Venus took a completely different development course.
Today the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the Venus Express space probe of the European Space Agency, which examined the plant for a year, provide a sobering view of how the earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express Mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data enable us to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago as the Earth, possibly with an indwelling environment."
