The history of premise is staggering, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York in 1964, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, produced hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: These were not from Warhol for cost reasons, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not works of art, but their role models, just exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo wood chests in Sweden, which, however, were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Zeitzeugen are now speaking of about fifteen crates, which at that time have been included in the art and auction history as authorised andy-warhol-brillo boxes called "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have achieved more than 100 000 dollars in auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later wrongly claimed that it had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol had then left him.
In fact Hultén's 105 crates were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at Moderna Museet, has also investigated three Swedish private owned Brillo boxes, of which two were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press circuit boards were first grounded and smelted, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the colour was applied directly to the press plate without any foundation - it is not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "serious allegations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, one has shrouded oneself there in unspeakable silence.
